            <h5 id="part1">Article 1: The nature and objectives of the game of gomoku</h5>
            <p>1.1 Checkers is a sports-logic game for two players who alternately place black and white stones on any unoccupied intersections of the "game board".<br>
                1.2 The game board is a network of 15 horizontal and 15 vertical lines forming 225 intersections.<br>
                1.3 Alternatively, crosses and circles can be used instead of black and white stones; instead of the game board, a playing area with the same number of fields corresponding to the parameters in article 1.2.<br>
                1.4 The player with the black stones starts (hereinafter referred to as the "starting player").<br>
                1.5 Players take turns in their turns. It is the player's turn after their opponent has made a move.<br>
                1.6 The goal of both players is to create an uninterrupted horizontal, vertical or diagonal (diagonal) row of exactly five stones of the same color.</p>
            <h5 id="part2">Article 2: Initiation of swap2</h5>
            <p>2.1 At the beginning of the game, it is determined which of the two players is the starting player.<br>
                2.2 The starting player places any three stones on the board in the order black, white, black.<br>
                2.3 The opponent then has the option to:<br>
                2.3.1 choose which color of stones he wants to play for, or<br>
                2.3.2 place two more stones on the board in the order white, black and leave the choice of color to the opponent (starting player), who will definitively determine the color of the stones of both players.<br>
                2.4 Subsequently, the player with the white stones makes his move and then the players take turns placing the stones until the end of the game.</p>
            <h5 id="part3">Article 3: Execution of the move</h5>
            <p>3.1 Making a move means placing a stone on one of the free intersections on the game board.<br>
                3.2 The starting position according to Article 2.2 and the choice of color or the placement of stones according to Article 2.3 are also considered to be the execution of a move.<br>
                3.3 If a player breaks contact with a currently placed stone, he may no longer move it or take it back.</p>
            <h5 id="part4">Article 4: Termination of the game</h5>
            <p>4.1 The game is won by the player who first creates exactly five stones in a row of the same color and announces it to the opponent. This immediately ends the game.<br>
                4.2 If the player creates exactly five stones in a row of the same color, but does not announce his win to the opponent, the game continues until the time of announcement or other end of the game.<br>
                4.3 If six or more stones of the same color are formed in a row, the game continues.<br>
                4.4 The game is won by the player whose opponent has declared surrender. This immediately ends the game.<br>
                4.5 The game ends in a draw if all intersections on the board are occupied. This immediately ends the game.<br>
                4.6 The game ends in a draw based on the agreement between the two players during the game, provided that both players have made at least one move. This immediately ends the game.</p>
            <h4 id="tournament">TOURNAMENT RULES</h4>
            <h5 id="part5">Article 5: Measurement of time</h5>
            <p>5.1 Clocks are used to measure time, which are equipped with two dials (displays), connected to each other in such a way that both cannot be in operation at the same time.<br>
                5.2 During the game, each player, after making his turn on the board, stops his clock and starts his opponent's clock. This completes the move.<br>
                5.3 A player may press his clock only after making his move.<br>
                5.4 The player must press his clock with the same hand he made the move.<br>
                5.5 Only the player whose clock is running may correct the inaccurate position of the stones.<br>
                5.6 Each player must complete all moves within the specified time period, or additional time may be set for each move.<br>
                5.7 In addition to the situations mentioned in articles 4.1, 4.2, 4.4, 4.5, 4.6, it applies that:<br>
                5.7.1 The game is won by the player who correctly announces that his opponent has used up the allotted time. This immediately ends the game.<br>
                5.7.2 The game ends in a draw if both players run out of time and neither player claims a win in accordance with Article 5.7.1 before running out of time. This immediately ends the game.<br>
                5.8 At the time designated for the start of the game, the starting player's clock will start.<br>
                5.9 If it is necessary to stop the game, the referee stops both clocks. A player may stop both clocks only in a justified case, when he needs the referee's help to solve an incorrectness or violation of the rules. The referee decides when the game should resume. If both clocks stop, a position on the game board must be covered.</p>
            <h5 id="part6">Article 6: Irregularities</h5>
            <p>6.1 If one or more stones appear on the board in violation of the rules and the stone/stones must be returned to their previous position, the arbiter shall adjust the setting of the clock to the best of his knowledge and conscience, with the option of leaving the time on the clock unchanged.<br>
                6.2 If the position was destroyed by the fault of one of the players and if it is possible to recreate it, the game is reconstructed at the expense of the running time of the culprit. If it cannot be recreated, the culprit has lost the game.<br>
                6.3 If it is not possible to reconstruct the damaged position and if none of the players is responsible for throwing, the game is invalid and a new one must be played.<br>
                6.4 If, during the game, it is discovered that the clock setting of one or both players is incorrect, the player or the referee shall stop the clock immediately. The referee sets the clock correctly and adjusts the time if necessary. The referee will set the clock to the best of his knowledge and conscience.</p>
            <h5 id="part7">Article 7: Recording moves</h5>
            <p>7.1 If the rules of the tournament so determine, each player is obliged during the game to record his moves and his opponent's moves in the record sheet as clearly and legibly as possible.<br>
                7.2 The player must have all the moves made on the board written down before making his own move. It is forbidden to write moves in advance.<br>
                7.3 The score sheet must be visible to the referee throughout the game.<br>
                7.4 Tournament rules may specify a time limit during which a player is no longer required to record moves during play. However, the player is obliged to complete his record sheet after the end of the game.<br>
                7.5 In the event of the situation referred to in Article 7.4, the player may ask one of the spectators to record the moves for him.<br>
                7.6 At the end of the game, the players state the result of the game, the number of the last move made and the remaining time of both players. He subsequently confirms the correctness of both recording sheets with his signature.</p>
